 SUMMARY                                                          9549 1451
    The cross section data file for neutron reactions with 243Am  9549 1451
 has been reevaluated over the incident neutron energy range from 9549 1451
 0.042 to 30 MeV.  Details of the analysis are given in the       9549 1451
 sections that follow.  Some general features of the work are:    9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 1. The ENDF/B-VI, Release 1, n + 243Am resonance parameters were 9549 1451
 adopted at neutron energies below 42 keV, suitably joined with   9549 1451
 the results of the present analysis at 42 keV.  Additionally,    9549 1451
 the evaluation by Howerton in ENDF/B-VI.1 was used for MT=3,18   9549 1451
 gamma-ray production data, and the radioactivity decay data in   9549 1451
 file 8 and 9 was taken over from ENDF/B-VI.1.                    9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 2.  A coupled-channel optical model potential was developed from 9549 1451
 analyses of nearby actinides that is consistent with             9549 1451
 measurements of the n + 241Am neutron total cross section.  After9549 1451
 an isospin correction, this potential was used in the n + 243Am  9549 1451
 analysis to calculate the neutron total cross section, elastic   9549 1451
 and inelastic scattering cross sections and angular              9549 1451
 distributions, and reaction cross sections and transmission      9549 1451
 coefficients for a theoretical analysis of the reaction          9549 1451
 channels.  The direct cross sections from the coupled-channel    9549 1451
 analysis were combined with compound nucleus calculations at     9549 1451
 lower energies and with preequilibrium theory calculations at    9549 1451
 higher energies.  Angular distributions for the first 13 excited 9549 1451
 states of 243Am were obtained from the direct, compound-nucleus, 9549 1451
 and preequilibrium calculations.  Energy-angle correlated        9549 1451
 distributions are provided for all continuum neutrons.           9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 3.  The evaluated fission cross section were obtained by making  9549 1451
 minor adjustments to the theoretical cross sections as needed to 9549 1451
 match the available experimental data.                           9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 4.  Values of prompt nubar were obtained from calculations by    9549 1451
 Madland [Ma94] using Madland-Nix theory.  The fission neutron    9549 1451
 spectra were taken from the n + 241Am ENDF/B-VI.3 evaluation,    9549 1451
 which was also based on Madland-Nix theory.  The latter will be  9549 1451
 replaced in the future with Madland-Nix calculations             9549 1451
 specifically for n + 243Am.                                      9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 THEORETICAL ANALYSIS                                             9549 1451
    The primary goal of the theoretical analysis was to provide   9549 1451
 a consistent set of data for all reactions over the energy range 9549 1451
 40 keV to 30 MeV.  In the case of n + 243Am, there are reasonable9549 1451
 experimental data available only for the fission (En < 10 MeV and9549 1451
 14 MeV) and radiative capture (En < 300 keV) cross sections.     9549 1451
 Therefore, the function of the theoretical analysis was to       9549 1451
 provide the total, elastic, inelastic, (n,2n), (n,3n) and (n,4n) 9549 1451
 cross sections, together with a smooth representation of the     9549 1451
 (n,f) and (n,g) cross sections, and the angular and energy       9549 1451
 distributions of secondary neutrons.  To accomplish this,        9549 1451
 parameters obtained in the theoretical analysis of n + 241Am     9549 1451
 reactions, performed earlier for the ENDF/B-VI.3 241Am           9549 1451
 evaluation, were utilized for 243Am, adjusting the relevant      9549 1451
 parameters to match the fission and (n,g) cross sections.        9549 1451
 Additionally, a theoretical analysis [Ma94] was performed to     9549 1451
 obtain the average neutron multiplicity from fission using the   9549 1451
 Madland-Nix formalism.  A similar analysis of the energy spectra 9549 1451
 of fission neutrons as a function of incident energy will be     9549 1451
 performed by D. Madland in the future.                           9549 1451
     Coupled-channel deformed optical model calculations were     9549 1451
 performed with the ECIS code [Ra70] over the incident neutron    9549 1451
 energy range from 0.001 to 30 MeV.  Hauser-Feshbach reaction     9549 1451
 theory calculations were carried out with the LANL version of    9549 1451
 the COMNUC code [Du70] at lower energies and the GNASH           9549 1451
 statistical/preequilibrium code [Yo92] at higher energies to     9549 1451
 obtain all partial reaction cross section data.  Both reaction   9549 1451
 theory codes used neutron transmission coefficients from the     9549 1451
 optical model analysis.                                          9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 A.  Optical Model                                                9549 1451
    The optical model potential was obtained by considering       9549 1451
 several coupled-channel parameterizations developed from         9549 1451
 n+235,238U and 239Pu experimental data [Ma78],[Yo88],[Yo92a].    9549 1451
 Parameters were adjusted until a reasonable fit to experimental  9549 1451
 data for the neutron total cross section of 241Am was obtained.  9549 1451
 The calculations for 243Am included the lowest five members of   9549 1451
 the 5/2- ground state rotational band, that is, the 7/2-, 9/2-,  9549 1451
 11/2- and 13/2-  excited states at Ex = 42, 96, 163 and 241 keV  9549 1451
 were coupled with the 5/2- ground state.                         9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 B.  Reaction Theory Calculations                                 9549 1451
    The Hauser-Feshbach statistical calculations were performed   9549 1451
 with the COMNUC [Du70] and GNASH [Yo92b] codes.  Both codes      9549 1451
 include a double-humped fission barrier model, using uncoupled   9549 1451
 oscillators for the barrier representation in GNASH and coupled  9549 1451
 or uncoupled oscillators in COMNUC, as described by Arthur       9549 1451
 [Ar82].  The COMNUC calculations include the possibility of      9549 1451
 width-fluctuation corrections and corrections for class II       9549 1451
 fluctuations [Ly74], which are needed at lower energies, whereas 9549 1451
 GNASH provides the preequilibrium corrections that are required  9549 1451
 at higher energies.  Accordingly, a combination of GNASH and     9549 1451
 COMNUC were used in the calculations below about 2 MeV, and the  9549 1451
 GNASH code alone was employed at higher energies using two       9549 1451
 uncoupled oscillators in the fission calculations.               9549 1451
    Each compound nucleus formed in the calculations is           9549 1451
 permitted to decay through the fission channel, by neutron       9549 1451
 emission, and by gamma-ray emission.  Neutron transmission       9549 1451
 coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations are obtained   9549 1451
 from the coupled-channel optical model.  Gamma ray transmission  9549 1451
 coefficients are obtained from gamma-ray strength functions      9549 1451
 calculated with the generalized Lorentzian model of Kopecky and  9549 1451
 Uhl [Ko90].  Transmission coefficients for fission are           9549 1451
 calculated from the fission model summarized here and detailed   9549 1451
 in [Yo92b].                                                      9549 1451
    Gilbert and Cameron [Gi70] phenomenological level density     9549 1451
 functions were used to represent continuum levels at ground-     9549 1451
 state deformations, appropriately matched to available           9549 1451
 experimental structure data at lower excitation energies.        9549 1451
 Multiplicative factors were applied to the level density         9549 1451
 functions to account for enhancements in the fission transition  9549 1451
 state densities at the fission barriers due to increased         9549 1451
 asymmetry conditions, and the continuum level densities were     9549 1451
 matched to the discrete fission transition states at each        9549 1451
 barrier.  The discrete fission transition state spectra were     9549 1451
 calculated from bandhead information taken from calculations and 9549 1451
 compilations by Britt [Br82] and by Nagel [Na91].                9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 DESCRIPTION OF EVALUATED DATA BASE                               9549 1451
 A.  Total Cross Section                                          9549 1451
     The evaluated total cross section below 42 keV is obtained   9549 1451
 from the earlier resonance parameter evaluation in ENDF/B-VI.1,  9549 1451
 suitably matched to the results of the current analysis at 30    9549 1451
 keV.  From 42 keV to 30 MeV, the coupled-channel deformed        9549 1451
 optical model calculations described above were utilized.        9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 B.  Elastic Cross Section                                        9549 1451
    The elastic cross section at all energies is obtained from    9549 1451
 the difference of the total and nonelastic cross sections.       9549 1451
 Below 42 keV it comes from the ENDF/B-VI.1 resonance parameters  9549 1451
 and at higher energies it is mainly determined by the coupled-   9549 1451
 channel optical model calculations.  Angular distributions for   9549 1451
 elastic neutrons were obtained at all energies from the coupled- 9549 1451
 channel calculations and are given as Legendre expansions.       9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 C.  Fission Cross Section                                        9549 1451
    Below an incident neutron energy of about 650 keV, the        9549 1451
 fission cross section was taken from the previous ENDF/B-VI.1    9549 1451
 evaluation, because they agree well with experimental data.  At  9549 1451
 higher energies the fission cross section was obtained by        9549 1451
 adjusting the results of the theoretical analysis to optimize    9549 1451
 agreement with experimental data.  At all energies the           9549 1451
 adjustment required was less than about 3 percent.  Above 5 MeV, 9549 1451
 the theoretical values were used directly.  Neutrons from        9549 1451
 fission are assumed to isotropic in the laboratory system.       9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 D.  Radiative Capture Cross Section                              9549 1451
    The radiative capture cross section is calculated using the   9549 1451
 generalized Lorentzian model of [Ko90]. The normalization of the 9549 1451
 strength function was set by requiring the calculated (n,g)      9549 1451
 cross section be consistent with measured values for 243Am.      9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
E.  Inelastic Neutron Cross Sections                              9549 1451
    Discrete (n,n') cross sections are included for the lowest    9549 1451
 13 excited states of 243Am.  The first, fourth, seventh,  and    9549 1451
 ninth excited states are members of the K = 5/2 ground-state     9549 1451
 rotational band and include coupled-channel as well as compound  9549 1451
 nucleus contributions.  The remaining discrete-state cross       9549 1451
 sections through the 13th excited state are combinations of      9549 1451
 compound nucleus and preequilibrium contributions and were       9549 1451
 calculated with the GNASH code.  Angular distributions for all   9549 1451
 the discrete inelastic neutrons are appropriate combinations of  9549 1451
 the compound nucleus, direct reaction, and preequilibrium        9549 1451
 contributions and are represented by Legendre expansions.        9549 1451
    The inelastic data corresponding to excitation energies in    9549 1451
 243Am above 0.383 MeV are given as energy-angle correlated       9549 1451
 continuous spectra and were calculated with the GNASH code.  The 9549 1451
 results are given in File 6 of the ENDF/B-formatted evaluation   9549 1451
 (ENDF-6 format) and utilize systematics by Kalbach [Ka88] for    9549 1451
 angular distribution information, parameterized in terms of      9549 1451
 preequilibrium ratios calculated in GNASH.                       9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
 F.  Cross Sections for 243Am(n,xn) Reactions                     9549 1451
    The 243Am(n,2n), (n,3n), and (n,4n) cross sections result     9549 1451
 entirely from the theoretical analysis and GNASH calculations.   9549 1451
 Energy-angle correlated distributions are given for all the      9549 1451
 243Am(n,xn) reactions, making use of Kalbach's systematics [Ka88]9549 1451
 and the ENDF-6 File 6 representation.                            9549 1451
                                                                  9549 1451
